WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.520
 Our next topic is to talk about login and logout.

00:00:02.520 --> 00:00:05.800
 Now just in general, I have this GitHub repository

00:00:05.800 --> 00:00:08.120
 called DJ4E Samples, and every once in a while

00:00:08.120 --> 00:00:11.520
 you oughta see if I've found some bugs and fixed 'em,

00:00:11.520 --> 00:00:13.560
 so go over to your samples and do a git pull.

00:00:13.560 --> 00:00:15.400
 So every once in a while, just do that.

00:00:15.400 --> 00:00:19.220
 So django, like in lots of situations,

00:00:19.220 --> 00:00:22.640
 comes with a built-in login/logout system.

00:00:22.640 --> 00:00:23.920
 There's lots of ways to do it.

00:00:23.920 --> 00:00:25.360
 You can read up on it.

00:00:25.360 --> 00:00:29.560
 It has a way to create users, has this nice admin interface,

00:00:29.560 --> 00:00:31.200
 and so one of the things we like about django

00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:32.200
 is that we don't have to build

00:00:32.200 --> 00:00:35.160
 some of these basic maintenance things.

00:00:35.160 --> 00:00:36.780
 It has permissions and groups.

00:00:36.780 --> 00:00:39.160
 We use this in the local library application,

00:00:39.160 --> 00:00:42.400
 but we're not gonna use that so much in our applications.

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:44.560
 And passwords, et cetera.

00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:46.360
 And it has a way to store these things

00:00:46.360 --> 00:00:48.580
 in various techniques.

00:00:48.580 --> 00:00:51.600
 And so the first thing that you'll probably encounter

00:00:51.600 --> 00:00:54.160
 when you're doing this is to create a superuser,

00:00:54.160 --> 00:00:56.080
 and so you have to log into your system.

00:00:56.080 --> 00:00:59.200
 You create a superuser, give it a name, an email address.

00:00:59.200 --> 00:01:01.840
 The email address is for password recovery,

00:01:01.840 --> 00:01:03.700
 even though you can log in and you can change

00:01:03.700 --> 00:01:07.200
 your superuser password anywhere.

00:01:07.200 --> 00:01:09.700
 And then you do it.

00:01:09.700 --> 00:01:13.960
 Now there's a great XKCD cartoon for so many things.

00:01:13.960 --> 00:01:17.100
 This is, one guy says, "Make me a sandwich,"

00:01:17.100 --> 00:01:19.480
 and the other one says, "What, make it yourself,"

00:01:19.480 --> 00:01:22.580
 and then says, "S-U-D-O, make me a sandwich."

00:01:22.580 --> 00:01:23.820
 And the other person says, "Okay."

00:01:23.820 --> 00:01:26.400
 So what S-U-D-O means is it's a Linux command

00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:28.840
 to switch to the superuser and do a command.

00:01:28.840 --> 00:01:31.640
 And so if you don't have permissions to do a command,

00:01:31.640 --> 00:01:35.540
 you can say sudo a command, and so that's what this XKCD.

00:01:35.540 --> 00:01:37.000
 So that's what we call a superuser.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:39.560
 That's the user that has all permissions,

00:01:39.560 --> 00:01:43.680
 doesn't need to get any special permissions.

00:01:43.680 --> 00:01:46.300
 This might be a good time to review what you're going to do

00:01:46.300 --> 00:01:47.480
 when you wipe out your database.

00:01:47.480 --> 00:01:50.320
 When you create that superuser, it just adds a row

00:01:50.320 --> 00:01:53.320
 into a table in your DBSQL light.

00:01:53.320 --> 00:01:56.360
 And you can wipe this out any time.

00:01:56.360 --> 00:02:00.680
 That's why I like using SQLite for development in Django.

00:02:00.680 --> 00:02:03.520
 If you remove it, you've removed all the tables,

00:02:03.520 --> 00:02:06.860
 all of the tables created by migrations.

00:02:06.860 --> 00:02:08.840
 The migrate command is what creates tables.

00:02:08.840 --> 00:02:11.060
 The make migration actually creates migrations

00:02:11.060 --> 00:02:13.160
 with your Python code.

00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:14.480
 So if you're going to start fresh,

00:02:14.480 --> 00:02:17.880
 you've got to remove the DBSQLite file.

00:02:17.880 --> 00:02:20.400
 That's got rid of all your users, all your superusers.

00:02:20.400 --> 00:02:22.680
 Any data you put in, it's gone.

00:02:22.680 --> 00:02:24.440
 And then you have to wake it back up

00:02:24.440 --> 00:02:27.520
 with a bunch of empty tables, with a manage.py migrate,

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:29.460
 and you'll see all those things.

00:02:29.460 --> 00:02:33.560
 Lots of lines come out at that point, I didn't include them.

00:02:33.560 --> 00:02:35.820
 And then you're gonna have to create your superusers again.

00:02:35.820 --> 00:02:38.120
 So just if you wipe your database,

00:02:38.120 --> 00:02:40.840
 you've got to recreate your superusers.

00:02:40.840 --> 00:02:43.000
 Once you have a superuser, the rest of the users

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:45.120
 are put in using the admin interface.

00:02:45.120 --> 00:02:47.840
 You just go in and among all the other models

00:02:47.840 --> 00:02:49.420
 that you might have in your application,

00:02:49.420 --> 00:02:51.240
 the groups and the users are just models.

00:02:51.240 --> 00:02:53.880
 They're models that happen to be built into Django,

00:02:53.880 --> 00:02:56.860
 and you don't have any responsibility for building them.

00:02:56.860 --> 00:03:00.840
 And so, like I said, the groups and permissions is useful,

00:03:00.840 --> 00:03:01.980
 and you can read up on that,

00:03:01.980 --> 00:03:04.600
 and maybe your application needs to use those.

00:03:04.600 --> 00:03:09.400
 But for me, I pretty much just make users and call it good.

00:03:09.400 --> 00:03:12.280
 Later, we're going to learn how to use social logins.

00:03:12.280 --> 00:03:14.280
 So we'll use GitHub to log people in,

00:03:14.280 --> 00:03:16.020
 so you don't have to create any users

00:03:16.020 --> 00:03:17.320
 other than your admin user.

00:03:17.320 --> 00:03:19.080
 But in the short term, we're just gonna use

00:03:19.080 --> 00:03:22.580
 what are called local users, which are stuck in a database,

00:03:22.580 --> 00:03:25.820
 kept in the database, and easy to create, easy to maintain.

00:03:25.820 --> 00:03:28.800
 But you tend to have to manually maintain them a little bit.

00:03:28.800 --> 00:03:31.400
 So next, we're gonna look at, now that you've got a user,

00:03:31.400 --> 00:03:35.560
 how do we, in our application code, log in and log out users.

00:03:35.560 --> 00:03:38.140
 (upbeat music)

